<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="389" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1117,1396]" box="[151,1386,1117,1144]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,1117,1143]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Description.</emphasis>
Brown, often with variable dark pattern on head, pro-, mesonotum, and forewings (
<figureCitation box="[1236,1374,1117,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Figs. 24–25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1117,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[508,524,1153,1167]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">nd</superScript>
tergite in male very short, separated by wide round notch (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1333,1153,1179]" captionStart="FIGURES 126–150" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,190,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-16@19.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionText="FIGURES 126–150. Macropsis milkoi (126–138), M. cerea (139–144), and M. viridobrunnea (145–150). 126, 130, 134, 139, 145―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 127–128, 131–132, 135–136, 140–141, 146–147—the 2nd sternite; 129, 133, 137, 142–143, 148–149―penis, lateral view; 138, 144, 150―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457946/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes triangular, separated by rounded notch (
<figureCitation box="[718,885,1189,1215]" captionStart="FIGURES 126–150" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,190,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-16@19.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionText="FIGURES 126–150. Macropsis milkoi (126–138), M. cerea (139–144), and M. viridobrunnea (145–150). 126, 130, 134, 139, 145―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 127–128, 131–132, 135–136, 140–141, 146–147—the 2nd sternite; 129, 133, 137, 142–143, 148–149―penis, lateral view; 138, 144, 150―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457946/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Figs. 140–141</figureCitation>
). Penis stem in side view wide, with slight if any extension in middle (
<figureCitation box="[387,554,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 126–150" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,190,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-16@19.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionText="FIGURES 126–150. Macropsis milkoi (126–138), M. cerea (139–144), and M. viridobrunnea (145–150). 126, 130, 134, 139, 145―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 127–128, 131–132, 135–136, 140–141, 146–147—the 2nd sternite; 129, 133, 137, 142–143, 148–149―penis, lateral view; 138, 144, 150―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457946/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Figs. 142–143</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[586,602,1225,1239]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor with 3–5 preapical teeth each (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1304,1225,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 126–150" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,190,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-16@19.[151,1436,181,1917]" captionText="FIGURES 126–150. Macropsis milkoi (126–138), M. cerea (139–144), and M. viridobrunnea (145–150). 126, 130, 134, 139, 145―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 127–128, 131–132, 135–136, 140–141, 146–147—the 2nd sternite; 129, 133, 137, 142–143, 148–149―penis, lateral view; 138, 144, 150―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457946" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457946/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Fig. 144</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1117,1396]" box="[199,942,1261,1288]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">
Body length (including tegmina): 
<specimenCount box="[580,603,1262,1288]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 4.5–5.0 mm; 
<specimenCount box="[765,786,1262,1288]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[800,938,1261,1288]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" metricValueMax="5.6" metricValueMin="4.9" pageId="8" pageNumber="389" unit="mm" value="5.25" valueMax="5.6" valueMin="4.9">4.9–5.6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,587,1297,1323]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1117,1396]" box="[199,587,1297,1323]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1297,1323]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Host.</emphasis>
On different willow species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="389" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1117,1396]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1333,1359]" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Distribution.</emphasis>
Transpalearctic within the forest zone. Common throughout the northern half of 
<collectingCountry box="[1268,1402,1333,1359]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="8" pageNumber="389">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
; in southeast was found only on Tarbagatai.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
